SkyComment: 100% Clear. Milky Way in area of the Summer Triangle asterism was only very slightly visible. Only a trained person with good eyesight would be needed to discern the Milky Way. Visual NELM estimated to be 4.3 to 4.5 based on star field counts in Ursa Minor and Pegasus. Andromeda Galaxy and Perseus Double Cluster was observed overhead, but averted vision was needed to see these objects. The stars of Orion and Pleiades were fairly visible in the eastern sky.
LocationComment: Cordorus State Park near Band Shell. Dry conditions, some dew. Area dotted by trees. Codorus State Park is a very suburban park with light domes along all horizon views. Eastern horizon appeared darkest. Horizon views likely impacted by Harrisburg to the North, York to the Northeast, Baltimore and Washington DC to the South, Hanover and Gettysburg to the West.  No outdoor dawn to dusk lights in immediate study area. Area illuminated by ambient light from surrounding cities/towns. Skyglow produced enough ambient light to where equipment could easily be discerned on the ground and field notebook markings could be read. Light domes extend 30 to 50 degrees above horizon - mostly in WNW from Hanover and Gettysburg. Tree lines at horizon level plainly visible. Hand placed at arms length in front of observer was plainly visible. Sky had a grayish-white appearance especially at the horizons and several degrees above.

SkyComment: 100% Clear.  Milky Way plainly visible overhead and extending to southwest. Sky is noticeably darker with very minor sky-glow to east-northeast and in southwest at tree-top level. Visual NELM estimated to be ~5 based on the seven main stars that make up Ursa Minor. All 7 stars were visible to the unaided eye and and/or with averted vision.
LocationComment: Dam area of Doubling Gap Lake. Lat: 40.282987, Long: -77.414700.   Utility building on east end of dam has a single light pole (Lat: 40.282920, -77.414163) owned by power company. Bulb appears to be low pressure sodium. Fixture is not full cutoff and contains an unshielded glass fixture. Light does spill onto the dam area and illuminates trees across lake (visible in long exposure photography) and casts shadows on dam area. Utility light is probably more noticeable when the foliage has fallen from the trees. During the summer months the tree foliage may shield the light more-so than at other times. Otherwise area is dark with some light glow to the south-southeast, perhaps from Carlise. Mountain ridge tree line easily around entire area. Tree tops extend up to approximately 15 to 20+ degrees - higher in south due to trees being in close proximity. Hand placed at arm's length in front of observer was plainly visible.

SkyComment: 100% Clear, Light wind ~5 to 8 mph. Dry conditions, very little if any dew. Although Kings Gap is elevated above the surrounding communities some light infiltrates the area especially from Carlisle to the north-northeast and to the west. The surrounding trees help to eliminate some of the glow allowing an appreciably dark sky to be viewed overhead - which allows some structure to be seen in the Milky Way.  However the trees also limit visibility of objects near the horizon.
LocationComment: Small grassy area across road and southeast of Mansion   (Lat: 40.093233, Long: -77.267726). Area is surrounded on all sides by trees. Tree tops extend up to approximately 25 to 30+ degrees in places surrounding site.

SkyComment: 100% clear. Light domes are particularly evident along the NNE horizons. Under dark transparent skies, some structure can be seen in the Milky Way, especially overhead, and surprisingly in some instances extending down to the tree tops around landing zone.
LocationComment: Open grassy area "Landing Zone - Overflow Parking" on east side of snack bar/restroom building and north of Fuller Lake.  Lat: 40.031509, Long: -77.297510
1 day after New Moon, clear sky, two street lights nearby behind trees.

SkyComment: There was about 1/4 if cloud cover. Due to this minimal amount, I was able to view an abundant amount of stars as shown in the Magnitude 2 chart above. The planet Venus and Jupiter were both visible. Venus was located in the North west while Jupiter was located in the South west, closer to the Leo constellation. A slight haze was present towards the west, however, it did no affect my observations. Specifically in the Leo constellation the Algieba and Regulus stars were most visible.
LocationComment: The viewing location was in a suburban area. During my observations, there was no light source with 50 m of my viewing location. Due to the lack of trees in the vicinity, I had a clear view of the sky. The absence of light ultimately created a good observation point.

SkyComment: Esta observación fue realizada en una noche sin nubosidad, pero si se presento una gran cúpula de luz por todo el cielo, la cual no permitía ver la noche con todo su esplendor. No habían objetos que obstaculizaran la visión de esta constelación, sin embargo la cúpula de luz que se hacia notar mas en las zonas horizontales  de mi posición no permitía observar otras porciones de cielo cercanas a esta.
LocationComment: Esta observación  fue realizada desde un placilla ubicada en la 26 1/2 oriente, la cual cuenta con un poste en el centro con 4 focos ( de los cuales solo uno funcionaba con normalidad y uno ocasionalmente), esta cuenta con un poste por esquina (con un foco cada uno), de los cuales solo estaba en funcionamiento el del lado sur-este. En esta locación se presentan de uno a dos postes por pasaje. Todos los postes de esta zona presentan una luz fuertemente amarilla, que contribuye enormemente a la cúpula de luz que se forma. La mayoría de las casas esta noche contaba con sus luces interiores prendidas, sin embargo un numero no menor a su vez con sus luces exteriores encendidas o luces de jardín.

LocationComment: 1040SP15GANonline  AST-1040-004 30041.201530  Jake Gentry  03/19/15  Live towards outskirts of city (Urban), lots of houses nearby. Climbed on roof to make observations. Was above street lights ( 3 total, 2 behind, 1 in front) and not a lot of glow in the sky. No trees or other objects obstructed my view of the sky from the roof.   In this Activity, I was looking forward to learning how to identify a certain constellation, in this case, the constellation of Orion. From my roof, Orion was surprisingly easy to locate. The clear sky was perfect for observing. I visited this website before going on the roof, and I was able to gain an idea of what exactly I was looking for. The 3 stars that make up "Orion's Belt" were not too hard to find. After finding those, I looked for  Betelgeuse, located above the belt, and found it. The reddish tint of Betelgeuse was very clear, and that aided in the process of confirming I was looking at the correct constellation. I would like to go out on a spate night, from a different location, and compare my results.
